additionalComments: generative AI might lead toward more compliant DMSPs but we don't know if they will be comprehensible to the researchers.  However, we already see many garbled DMSPs without the help of gen AI so I don't think it will make things worse in most cases.
It can be useful, but manual follow-up is necessary to ensure its accuracy and catch any missing components.
It seems like a great time-saver for researchers who have the familiarity to critique the outputs. I'm less sure about those who use it to replace reading up on what the DMSP is meant to be about.
Can be used as collaborative tool to improve clarity, consistency, and tone, especially for researchers who may not be native English speakers.

I think as in any academic context, it is critical to review the output of AI tools to ensure the accuracy and suitability of any content that ends up in final copies. I also believe it should be clearly stated in the document if and to what extent AI was used.

Although I have rarely used AI to help investigators complete their DMSPs due to my own familiarity and expertise with the NIH DMSP elements, I am not opposed to it. Ravi Ravichandran, Program Director at NIDDK, initially worked on developing a ChatGPT-based DMSP tool for researchers but later shifted his focus to building an evaluation tool for NIH program officers. I have seen examples where this tool generates element-specific evaluation scores and action items, which is promising. Many NIH program officers are not deeply familiar with all six DMSP elements, so such tools could help level the field and ensure fair, consistent evaluations. In this context, DMPTool is well positioned to support researchers directly by offering an AI-enabled assistant to help them draft strong DMSPs.

AI seems to me, to be the love child of Albert Einstein and Donald Trump. Very intelligent, very knowledgeable, but if it doesn't know the answer, will pull it out of thin air and present it as god-given truth

additionalComments: Great idea, especially if it can be a minimal UX interface that is knowledgeable of the agency / funding call and asks researchers prompts to populate content, make recommendations for standards/ domain repos. All with a human in the loop and lots of references/documentation.
